Right — `ProviderOutput` implements `Drop` (for zeroization), so we can't move fields out. The correct approach: clone the token into SecretString, then let ProviderOutput's Drop zeroize its copy. This is the exact pattern you'd want at a secret boundary — the ProviderOutput's zeroizing Drop handles cleanup of the plain String copy.
[0m← [0mEdit src/token_convert.rs
Index: /home/ben/Documents/repos/noscope/src/token_convert.rs
===================================================================
--- /home/ben/Documents/repos/noscope/src/token_convert.rs
+++ /home/ben/Documents/repos/noscope/src/token_convert.rs
@@ -54,11 +54,14 @@
     role: &str,
     token_id: Option<String>,
     provider: &str,
 ) -> ScopedToken {
-    // NS-019: Wrap raw token in SecretString for zeroization guarantees.
-    // The ProviderOutput's own Drop will also zeroize its copy.
-    let secret = SecretString::from(output.token);
+    // NS-019: Clone the raw token into SecretString for zeroization guarantees.
+    // We must clone because ProviderOutput implements Drop (for zeroization),
+    // and Rust doesn't allow moving fields out of a Drop type. This is fine:
+    // ProviderOutput's Drop will zeroize its String copy, and SecretString
+    // manages zeroization of its own copy independently.
+    let secret = SecretString::from(output.token.clone());
 
     ScopedToken::new(secret, role, output.expires_at, token_id, provider)
 }
 

